segments.text: I was born and raised in Brazos County.
My people settled in Brazos County in about 1872.
My grandfather settled up on top of this hill.
I am now 83 years old.
Okay, so that makes what year were you born in?
And your full name is?
Noah C. Cole.
Well, Mr. Cole, you said your grandfather settled up there on the hill.
What brought him to this area?
They came from Alabama down here in Texas.
I don't know if they were hunting, but I lied, I guess.
That's a lie.
What kind of occupation was your grandfather in?
Farmers.
Farmers and ranchers.
So they just moved down here?
Do you know what crops they grew or have any idea?
Yes.
People, when they first came here, this land wasn't settled in mostly cattle range, mostly cattle range and wild cattle and things like that, but they all produced crops, raised farm products.
Cotton and corn and other things like that.
Okay, so then is, you know, like when your father came along, what was his, did he do ranching too?
Yes, he did ranching.
He bought land and owned land.
On the gin.
Really?
Yes.
We have a gin down there, old gin down there that he bought.
They raised considerable cotton.
Of course at that time they didn't have the the machinery that we have today.
We use horses and mules.
And no
up-to-date cultivators or anything like that.
So you just stayed in this area then?
And we had tenant farmers here.
My daddy had a good many tenant farmers that raised cotton and corn.
He accumulated quite a bit of land around.
And so then as you grew up you just kind of fell in his footsteps?
Yeah, I fell in his footsteps.
And we was in eight miles, uh, well you might put it in six miles of A&M College.
And one of my cousins that raised right up here on the other side of us, he was the director of A&M College at one time.
D.S.
Buchanan.
So, um, did you attend school or did you?
I attended the, uh, we had
country schools at that time, and I went from the country schools here to Sam Houston State Normal.
And I finished at Sam Houston State Normal in 1913.
Taught school a good many years.
Well, did you, did you marry later on then?
Yes, I married after the World War I. I enlisted in World War I. I was in the World War I, and
And when I came back from World War I, I married one of the neighbor girls around here.
Let me get her name right.
Clara Boykin Jones.
That was my wife.
Her people lived across the road.
Yeah.
I've known her all my life.
So did y'all, did you bring your children?
Did y'all have children?
We didn't have any children.
We didn't, unfortunately never had any children.
And she died getting many years ago.
Oh, okay.
And I continued on to live here.
I had lots of brothers and sisters.
I had three brothers and two sisters.
Oh.
Well are they all still in this immediate area?
They're all dead except me.
Oh, so what did they, were your brothers involved in ranching too?
Yes, my brother, well I had one, my older brother was a district clerk for Brazos County for many years, and he retired from that, but he's dead now.
And I had one sister, taught school in the surrounding areas for years, and I did too.
Oh, that's interesting.
She was a teacher in Brown High for years.
Do you have any idea what year she started teaching there?
Oh, I don't know what year she started teaching, but she taught all of her life.
And she was 87 years old, 85 years old when she died, sunshine cold.
Well, you said you were into ranching and everything.
What kind of changes has there been made since you started, you know, as far as technology and stuff like that?

Well, it was mostly the ranching, and really from the ranching, as the country settled, as the people settled in here, they began to raise the crops of cotton and corn and things that went along with it.
And we raised cotton and corn
for years until we might say along, well, I believe I was still, we were still farming here in 19, we might say 1915, 20.
And I went to war in 1917, came back, still continue to farm,
We had some mighty hard years later on.
So speaking of those hard years, can you remember the Depression?
Yes, I don't know exactly what year it was.
I imagine from 1925 and what we'd call 1925 or 1930, and there was some mighty hard, dry years.
It didn't rain for two years.
and our stock water oil would drop.
We didn't have the tanks and things in there that we have now.
We didn't have the wells.
And the government came in, very good to us, helped us to build tanks, wells.
Okay, well then later on in the late 30s, middle 30s, did the depression affect you, the national depression?
Oh yes, I guess so to a certain extent.
What, did y'all continue to farm, or did you have to find other work?
Yes, we just continued to farm.
We were right on.
Okay.
Did the government help you through that?
Yes, the government helped.
The government, I didn't, I wasn't needing any help at that time, but the government had WPA labor.
They had to build some of the schoolhouses.
And, not only that, we, and during
Roosevelt administration, which one of those presidents, wasn't Teddy, was it, what was it, D. Franklin?
Franklin.
Franklin D. Roosevelt, I believe.
We had what we, times and conditions were hard.
We killed cattle.
I killed calves and fired out of the head, hauled them over in the pasture.
I killed young cows.
We plowed up the cotton, destroyed it.
Well, as you, you know, as you grew older and everything, can you remember any famous figures coming to, you know, Bryan College Station area, such as maybe politicians or something?
Oh, yes, I do.
There's one of my kinfolk, some of my kinfolk, W.S.
Byrne, George Byrne, was Speaker of the House, was a representative.
during some of those years, and now he's still alive, practicing law in Brown.
Yeah.
Oh, and I remember many, Law Henderson.
I especially remember one man that was affiliated, that worked with the foreman class of people, that was Mr. Beeson.
He was the county agent of Rattlers County.
And he did work then that they're redoing right now.
He killed cows.
He taught us how to kill caves and cows and to process them.
And we used the process at that time.
We'd kill those caves and make them up in chili and can it.
We had home canners.
We'd can those stuff, can that stuff up, meats.
Right here?
Yes, in your own home.
I have one of my old kennels here in my house right today.
And we raised our hogs.
We had our meat.
We raised our vegetables.
My wife was a great hand with the home demonstration agent.
They canned everything we needed.
We didn't have the
At that time, we didn't have the deep freeze, you see.
And then, of course, later on this time, come on down, we used the deep freeze.
Okay, well, can you remember when the railroad came through Bryan County?
No, I don't remember, but I had my grandfather, I had a bed that my grandfather brought over here to Milligan.
It first stopped at the little town of Milligan down here.
little college and but I don't remember what year it came through here.
Okay so did it influence your your occupation your ranching occupation in any way?
No not any more than just town built up and the first courthouse was established first court was here down here on about three miles down the road down here then they moved it on up
And then they moved it on up to Boom, Boom, Boom.
That's the town up there called Boom.
Okay, well, for social activities, what type of did y'all engage in?
Well, practically the same thing they do today.
We had parties and things like that.
We didn't have no automobiles until about 1917, a little after 1917.
Can you remember the first automobile that came?
I remember the first one I got, and I was going to school in Huntsville when the doctor in Huntsville had a car, and he had, the only car he had, he had a dog.
It always run ahead of that thing.
When I came back from World War I, I had, I bought a 1917 Ford, me and my brother.
We said I wanted you in World War I.
And I bought a 1917 Ford, and I've been buying Fords ever since.
So then your social life was pretty much, was church an influence in your life?
Yes, church.
We had a church up here right up the road here, a pretty good Baptist church that was organized by my people.
And I've been deacon in that church ever since I was large enough.
My grandfather, my grandmother, my dad, my mother, several brothers and sisters were buried right up here side the road.
Broughton High Tribal Baptist Church.
OK. Well, so all of your folks were just relatively from around this same area?
They just, they never?
Well, they came all the, they came in from everywhere.
My mother, I had one group she knew, different communities like Steep Hollow was a, we had kin folks in the Steep Hollow community, the Dansmans, the Peters.
And all the old, old families that was originally here.
My book, I have a book on those people that were sitting.
So Mr. Peters is related to you then, is that?
Mm-hmm.
His grandfather, my grandmother's brothers and sisters.
Oh, I see the connection now.
Oh, okay.
He was down the other day.
We played dominoes, he and I and his brother and a fellow over there in college over there, Marco.
We played dominoes.
It was a Tuesday night.
He and our partner, we played dominoes this past time.
So what about Christmas time?
Has Christmas changed any since you were younger?
Oh, no, just about the same.
We had parties to the community and things like that.
One of the greatest things I can remember that affected all of us, we used to, years ago, the water proposition was a scarce proposition, and the lights, you see.
We had to cut stone wood, cook on the stove, and my old home was right across the road, 240 acres over there.
Well did the, speaking of lights and running water and everything, how did y'all cope?
We didn't have lights and running water.
How did y'all cope?
We had well water systems.

Okay, well then later on is... Then later on we, the governor kept to put in some tanks and during those hard times, you might call it during the Depression, I'd say during the Depression, he put in tanks and
And of course as we telephones increased, the REA came in, and we of course all began to modernize our homes, you see.
There's only one home in this community that I remember that I can say this offhand is still standing.
That's a house right down there, a nice house, been well kept, but all the rest of the homes
I've been torn down and rebuilt, you see.
Okay, this house that doesn't have it, that is still the same, is anyone living in this house?
No, it belongs to the Williams State down there, a big place down there.
They've kept it up.
No one's living in it, right?
No one.
They have it furnished.
They come out and stay during the weekend and things like that.
Big ranch on it.
Okay, well this book, The Baron, is that the title of the book?
That's the history of the Byrne family.
Okay, how did that come to be written?
Do you have any?
Some of the Byrnes, they wanted to write it.
There's a lady here in town.
Okay, is that about your folks?
Yeah, my people in there.
My mother was, she was connected with the Byrnes.
She was, this book was, they originally came from Alabama.
And this Barron gives a live history of the Barron families and the different connections of all in the county.
And she was one of the, she was a Soules.
And that was one of the beginning of the Barron family, the Soules.
So she was connected to the Barron's three?
She connected to, we connected to the Barron's soldiers, and then everybody else in town, in the county.
Todd's.
So that book was just written by someone?
The one with the family.
Oh, okay.
Well, do you remember, how about school?
Was it, what did you think of school?
Oh, well, school then was just like I taught school.
School then was just about like it is.
Well, it's of course more modernized now like that.
We had out there, we had three teachers.
We had three teachers, a principal and two assistants that taught school.
I taught there several years, and then I taught in different communities.
Okay, well, do you remember any of the people that
You know, were your teachers, say, in school?
Oh yeah, I remember I got students all around the country.
Okay, well what about when you were a student?
Do you remember any, like who was your teachers or principal at that time?
Oh yes, one of our principal teachers I tell you was E.K.
Barton.
He was a
Fine teacher.
I believe he's dead now, but he had people living around overstate.
He married into one of the families out there, married into the Jones families, and they've got people living around.
Do you remember any of your other teachers or people that influenced you?
Well, I can't recall too many of them right now that I went to school to.
I remember the teachers more than I. I spent three years down at the hospital.
I remember the Estill, President Estill down there, and different teachers down there.
It's a normal, it was a normal at that time, and later on it was added, made into a college, you see, in 1913 when I graduated.
It was a normal school, a teacher school.
Well, when you were in, you know, at the same Houston Normal, was it, did you work at that time, or did you just go to college?
I went to college, I boarded down there.
Okay, what, did they have dormitory facilities?
Yes, they had, no, they lived in private homes, most of them, different homes around there, boarding the students, you see.
Well, what was your, how were you fixed up to stay there?
I was, I was a 10 or 15 boy,
The girl, well the girl had separate dormitories, separate homes, and the boys down there.
What was your main college, your main course of study there?
I took, well I don't know what you would call that.
We had some manual training.
We had, and
Just a general education more for teachers.
Sam Houston Normal was a normal to produce teachers.
Oh, I see.
Okay, so it was just more or less a teacher college.
Yeah, it was a teacher college, and then later on it came into a regular... Began to offer more programs.
More courses.
It's a big school, isn't it?
Yes, it is.
Around the period of World War I, you mentioned that you enlisted and everything.
Did you, how did that affect your life?
Around World War I?
World War I?
Well, when we came back from World War I, I was in the Navy, and I got my discharge from Camden, New Jersey.
Battleship
I was waiting for the battleship Utah to go into commission.
I got my discharge plan and came back and take my place right over in the community as I did beforehand.
I done been to school you see then and I would get to teach some of the smaller schools, some of the schools around in the different parts of the
counties, different county, Owen Grimes County, some over here.
I taught right over here in the south of A&M College for three years.
There's a place out there known as Union Hill.
But we raised cattle and we had to fight the pest, the tick people and everything like that all through those things.
Well what, how did y'all go about fighting it?
What kind of
problems did y'all have as y'all raised, tried to raise cattle and everything?
We had what they called Texas fever ticks.
And we, they kept cows that wasn't immune from it would die.
And we had to, we built dipping vats and we dipped those cows for those ticks every two weeks.
And we finally eliminated the fever ticks
Yeah, in Texas.
What did y'all use as a dip?
Do you remember?
We used arsenic.
And just dipped the cattle in the arsenic?
Yes, sir.
We dipped those cows and run those cows through those dipping vats.
We still got those dipping vats today.
But we don't use them when we use spraying outfits now.
We don't.
We got rid of the fever tiki in Texas.
A&M College used to have a fence around us where they called it tic proof.
So many people
keep ticks with that cross.
Well did that, was there any other thing that plagued your cattle?
Oh yeah, all kind of insects.
And then we had the screwworms that's been put in just last few years, been one of the greatest things for the cattlemen we had.
We, they eliminated the screwworm.
How'd they go about doing that?
Well they, they took, they caught these
flies.
You know, it was a male fly and a female fly that laid the eggs.
And they treated, they caught these flies, they built the great big things around it.
One of the bitches in Texas is around over there.
And, and they sterilized, sterilized those flies, you see.
And they spread them out.
And they wouldn't hatch, you see.
And that eliminated the school worms.
We used to have to dock the worms every year.
It was a proposition, a big proposition.
That was one of the great benefits of the government.
Did they come in and help y'all?
Oh, they did that.
Yeah, they helped in that dipping business.
We had to dig those vats.
We had a regular dipping inspector to see the people that lived there for 14 days.
Were they, they were commissioned by the government to come out and do that?
Well, then other men came in and helped you?
I mean, how did y'all handle that?
Did the men from the community get together?
Well, we just went together and handled it.
One father maybe take his own cows, drive his own cows there.
Maybe some, each one drove his own cattle to the vats so they wouldn't get them mixed up, you see.
Oh, how'd y'all get your cows to market, or did you market them, or?
The railroad shipped to Dallas.
Oh, through the railroad?
Mm-hmm.
We didn't have the, at first we didn't have the, we didn't have the, like we had that auction range and things like that, you see.
That came on later on, you see.
Well did the, we said, you mentioned when you were younger did the, about farming, did the boll weevil have any effect on the process?
Oh yes, the boll weevil was one of the pests we had to deal with.
It put the cotton farmer nearly out of business.
And, of course, we fought the bull wheel just like we fought everything else, and they're still fighting.
Well, did that affect your father specifically?
Oh, yes, it affected everybody that lived there.
If it wasn't for the bull wheel, we could make two bales cut to an acre, but the bull wheel, we different control methods are used and by cultivation and things like that.
The boll weevil certainly was.
The many insects and things we had, cotton, leafworm, and things like that.
You have all those things.
Well, how did y'all, what did y'all use to control the boll weevil?
Do you have, can you remember?
They used poison, kind of a poison.
And the hardest thing in the world to kill, you put one between two blocks of ice and it wouldn't kill you.
My gosh.
Well, what kind of poison was it, do you know?
I don't know what the name they used.
Poison.
OK, for the continuation of this tape, please turn it over.
